Class CsvScheme

    Traceable, Serializable

    public class CsvScheme
extends Scheme<org.apache.hadoop.mapred.JobConf,org.apache.hadoop.mapred.RecordReader,org.apache.hadoop.mapred.OutputCollector,Object[],Object[]>
    The CSV scheme provides support for parsing and formatting CSV files using Apache Commons CSV.

    This scheme is designed for use a source or a sink in a Hadoop MR2 flow.

    To use the scheme, simply construct a new instance, passing either the Fields or a CSVFormat defining the structure of the CSV file. 

       CSVFormat format = CSVFormat.newFormat(',')
       .withHeader("user_id", "first_name", "last_name")
       .withSkipHeaderRecord(true);
     CsvScheme scheme = new CsvScheme(format);
     Tap tap = new Hfs(scheme, "hdfs://users.csv");

    The CSV scheme changes its behavior according to the Fields or CSVFormat provided to the constructor.

    For sources, this scheme detects headers and applies values to fields according to a set of rules based on the arguments provided. Generally speaking, headers define the columns as they are present in the underlying CSV file, and Fields specify how those columns should be presented to Cascading. The scheme may automatically detect CSV header information depending on the fields and headers provided to this constructor.

    Users can provided different combinations of Fields and CSVFormat.getHeader() values to control the input and output of the scheme. The rules that the scheme uses to resolve Fields and headers for sources are as follows:

    • If Fields is Fields.UNKNOWN and CSVFormat.getHeader() is null or empty and CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is false, the scheme assigns positional names to the columns (e.g. col1, col2, col3) and perform no additional validation.
    • If Fields is Fields.UNKNOWN and CSVFormat.getHeader() is null or empty but CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is true, the scheme will automatically detect the CSV headers using the first record in the file and perform no further validation.
    • If Fields are defined, CSVFormat.getHeader() is null or empty and CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is true, the scheme will detect the header from the first record in the CSV file and verify that the provided Fields names are present in the header names.
    • If Fields are defined, CSVFormat.getHeader() is null or empty and CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is false, the scheme will verify that the number of provided fields matches the number of provided columns.
    • If Fields are defined and CSVFormat.getHeader() are defined, the scheme will verify that the provided headers match the number of values in the first record in the CSV file, and verify that the provided field names are all present in the header names.
    • If Fields are Fields.UNKNOWN and CSVFormat.getHeader() is defined, the scheme will verify that the provided headers match the number of values in the first record in the CSV file and assign header names to unknown Fields.
    Similarly, the differences between sink Fields and headers allows users to control how fields are written to CSV files. The rules that the scheme uses to resolve Fields and headers are as follows:
    • If CSVFormat.getHeader() is defined and CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is true, the provided header record will be written to the output CSV file(s).
    • If CSVFormat.getHeader() is not defined and CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is true, the input Fields will be written to the CSV file(s) as the header.
    • If CSVFormat.getSkipHeaderRecord() is false, no header will be written to the output file(s).
    • If both sink Fields and headers are defined, all field names must be present in the output header record. When tuples are written out to the CSV file, any fields not present in the header record will be written as null. You can configure the output null string via CSVFormat.withNullString(String)
    Internally, CsvScheme uses CsvInputFormat and CsvOutputFormat for sourcing and sinking data respectively. These custom Hadoop input/output formats allow the scheme complete control over the encoding, compression, parsing, and formatting of bytes beneath Cascading's abstractions.
